shaped the larger moral discourse surrounding production and consumption, influencing how slavery and freedom came to be defined in the market economy. But ethical commerce was not without its ironies; the search for supplies of goods “not made by slaves”—including East India sugar—expanded the reach of colonial empires in the relentless pursuit of cheap but “free” labor.Not Made by Slaves illuminates the early years of global consumer society, while placing the politics of antislavery firmly in the history of capitalism. It is also a stark reminder that the struggle to ensure fair trade and labor conditions continues.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aAntislavery movementszAtlantic Ocean RegionxHistoryy19th century. 0aBusiness ethicszAtlantic Ocean RegionxHistoryy19th century. 0aCapitalismxMoral and ethical aspectszAtlantic Ocean RegionxHistoryy19th century. 0aConsumption (Economics)xMoral and ethical aspectszAtlantic OceanRegionxHistoryy19th century. 0aSocial responsibility of businesszAtlantic Ocean RegionxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / United States / Civil War Period (1850-1877).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069005740uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/978067425009340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674250093423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674250093.jpg  a978-3-11-069005-7  Harvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles